WEBVTT

NOTE
This file was generated by Descript <www.descript.com>

00:00:05.160 --> 00:00:07.960
Hello, hello, hello, and welcome

00:00:07.960 --> 00:00:09.770
to English Learning for Curious

00:00:09.770 --> 00:00:12.760
Minds, by Leonardo English, the show

00:00:12.770 --> 00:00:14.549
where you can listen to fascinating

00:00:14.550 --> 00:00:17.480
stories and learn weird and wonderful

00:00:17.490 --> 00:00:19.410
things about the world at the same

00:00:19.410 --> 00:00:21.079
time as improving your English.

00:00:21.619 --> 00:00:24.730
I'm Alastair Budge, and today it’s the

00:00:24.730 --> 00:00:27.950
start of another three-part mini-series,

00:00:28.230 --> 00:00:31.310
this time on animals throughout history.

00:00:31.689 --> 00:00:34.220
In part one, today’s episode, we’ll

00:00:34.220 --> 00:00:36.730
be talking about dogs, our canine

00:00:36.730 --> 00:00:39.169
companions, man’s best friend.

00:00:39.600 --> 00:00:42.450
Then in part two, we’ll talk about a very

00:00:42.530 --> 00:00:45.050
different but equally important animal.

00:00:45.370 --> 00:00:46.100
The cat.

00:00:46.560 --> 00:00:48.350
And in part three it’ll be

00:00:48.350 --> 00:00:50.580
the history of an animal that

00:00:50.590 --> 00:00:53.110
didn’t exist at all: the dragon.

00:00:53.669 --> 00:00:55.819
OK then, let's not waste a

00:00:55.829 --> 00:00:58.459
minute and get right into it.

00:00:59.779 --> 00:01:03.519
In Homer’s epic book, the Odyssey, the

00:01:03.519 --> 00:01:07.119
hero Odysseus spends ten long years

00:01:07.319 --> 00:01:10.409
away from home fighting the Trojan War.

00:01:11.549 --> 00:01:14.559
His ten-year journey back home is

00:01:14.619 --> 00:01:17.359
equally hazardous, and he has to

00:01:17.359 --> 00:01:21.089
evade cyclopes, giants, sorceresses,

00:01:21.379 --> 00:01:24.379
and various gods who mean him harm.

00:01:25.329 --> 00:01:28.499
In his absence, he is presumed dead,

00:01:28.869 --> 00:01:32.179
and his wife and son are left to deal

00:01:32.379 --> 00:01:35.009
with a group of men who have their eyes

00:01:35.009 --> 00:01:38.587
set on Odysseus’ loyal wife, Penelope.

00:01:39.338 --> 00:01:42.809
Odysseus does finally return home,

00:01:43.159 --> 00:01:47.259
but he must do so in secret, fearful

00:01:47.499 --> 00:01:49.629
that revealing his identity too

00:01:49.629 --> 00:01:53.299
soon would put him in mortal danger.

00:01:54.259 --> 00:01:57.879
So, he returns not in the clothes

00:01:57.999 --> 00:02:01.449
of a triumphant king, but disguised

00:02:01.679 --> 00:02:05.439
as a poor beggar clad in rags.

00:02:07.109 --> 00:02:10.009
True to his plan, nobody

00:02:10.059 --> 00:02:11.809
recognises their former king.

00:02:12.349 --> 00:02:13.969
Not his servants, not his

00:02:13.979 --> 00:02:15.799
wife, not even his son.

00:02:16.539 --> 00:02:19.549
Or rather, no human recognises

00:02:19.549 --> 00:02:20.789
their former master.

00:02:21.759 --> 00:02:24.129
As Odysseus makes his way towards his

00:02:24.129 --> 00:02:27.579
former palace, he comes across an old

00:02:27.589 --> 00:02:30.739
dog lying on the side of the road.

00:02:31.989 --> 00:02:34.529
The dog is lying in piles of

00:02:34.539 --> 00:02:36.819
filth, and covered in fleas.

00:02:38.213 --> 00:02:41.779
Odysseus recognises him as Argos,

00:02:42.163 --> 00:02:44.909
his old faithful hunting dog.

00:02:46.369 --> 00:02:48.599
Argos notices the beggar walking

00:02:48.599 --> 00:02:51.619
past, drops his ears, lifts

00:02:51.619 --> 00:02:54.199
his head and wags his tail.

00:02:55.329 --> 00:02:58.959
It has been twenty years, and Argos

00:02:59.199 --> 00:03:02.819
is old and dying, but the animal

00:03:02.879 --> 00:03:05.569
recognises his master immediately.

00:03:06.439 --> 00:03:09.449
He is too old and weak to get up, and

00:03:09.639 --> 00:03:12.269
Odysseus knows that he cannot greet

00:03:12.269 --> 00:03:15.009
him, lest his identity be revealed.

00:03:15.723 --> 00:03:19.149
Odysseus, the great Greek warrior, is

00:03:19.149 --> 00:03:22.699
forced to wipe the tears from his eyes.

00:03:23.969 --> 00:03:26.779
The narrator tells us that as soon as

00:03:26.829 --> 00:03:30.279
Odysseus sets foot in the palace, his

00:03:30.289 --> 00:03:34.799
loyal dog, Argos, keels over and dies.

00:03:36.189 --> 00:03:37.679
It’s one of the most memorable

00:03:37.689 --> 00:03:41.049
scenes in the Odyssey, and a reminder

00:03:41.249 --> 00:03:44.029
of how long and how deeply dogs

00:03:44.159 --> 00:03:45.909
have been part of the human story.

00:03:46.939 --> 00:03:49.379
Because Homer didn’t include

00:03:49.379 --> 00:03:50.719
this scene to show us that

00:03:50.729 --> 00:03:53.529
dogs are cute, or sentimental.

00:03:54.339 --> 00:03:58.059
He included it because, even nearly

00:03:58.119 --> 00:04:01.069
three thousand years ago, the idea

00:04:01.079 --> 00:04:03.179
that a dog would recognise its human,

00:04:03.359 --> 00:04:06.609
even after decades apart, already

00:04:06.609 --> 00:04:10.179
felt completely natural, so natural

00:04:10.639 --> 00:04:12.509
that it needed no explanation.

00:04:13.299 --> 00:04:16.019
Compared to every other animal–cats,

00:04:16.579 --> 00:04:19.639
horses, even your pet goldfish–the

00:04:19.639 --> 00:04:21.899
lives of dogs and humans are

00:04:21.899 --> 00:04:23.779
more closely intertwined.

00:04:24.359 --> 00:04:27.799
So, to understand this connection,

00:04:27.849 --> 00:04:30.329
to understand the history of dogs,

00:04:30.679 --> 00:04:32.999
we first need to go back to a

00:04:32.999 --> 00:04:35.340
time before dogs existed at all.

00:04:36.019 --> 00:04:38.249
A time when humans were not

00:04:38.409 --> 00:04:39.969
at the top of the food chain.

00:04:40.379 --> 00:04:42.429
A time when the night was far

00:04:42.429 --> 00:04:44.279
more dangerous than it is today.

00:04:45.519 --> 00:04:48.159
Imagine, if you will, the world

00:04:48.289 --> 00:04:50.639
thirty or forty thousand years ago.

00:04:51.619 --> 00:04:53.989
This was the Pleistocene, an

00:04:53.999 --> 00:04:56.909
era of ice and giant beasts.

00:04:57.439 --> 00:04:59.359
Humans were nomadic

00:04:59.579 --> 00:05:01.919
hunter-gatherers, moving across

00:05:01.959 --> 00:05:04.129
the landscape in small groups.

00:05:04.639 --> 00:05:07.129
By day, we were capable hunters,

00:05:07.369 --> 00:05:10.129
but by night, we were vulnerable.

00:05:10.819 --> 00:05:14.469
We had no walls, no lights, and we were

00:05:14.469 --> 00:05:16.719
surrounded by predators who could see

00:05:16.729 --> 00:05:18.879
in the dark much better than we could.

00:05:19.349 --> 00:05:22.769
There were cave bears, large cats, and

00:05:23.199 --> 00:05:26.659
various species of wolf–not the modern

00:05:26.939 --> 00:05:29.129
grey wolf you might see in a documentary

00:05:29.129 --> 00:05:33.059
today, but larger, now-extinct ancestors.

00:05:34.079 --> 00:05:36.599
Now, for a long time, the

00:05:36.819 --> 00:05:39.479
"standard" story of how wolves

00:05:39.499 --> 00:05:41.859
became dogs was quite simple.

00:05:42.349 --> 00:05:45.339
It went like this: a brave human

00:05:45.359 --> 00:05:47.719
hunter found a litter of wolf

00:05:47.719 --> 00:05:50.539
cubs, took one home, and raised it.

00:05:51.039 --> 00:05:52.959
Over generations, these

00:05:53.189 --> 00:05:55.359
"tame" wolves became dogs.

00:05:56.739 --> 00:05:59.039
It’s a nice story, but most

00:05:59.069 --> 00:06:01.039
modern scientists believe it

00:06:01.039 --> 00:06:02.979
is almost certainly wrong.

00:06:03.889 --> 00:06:04.349
Why?

00:06:04.939 --> 00:06:08.539
Well, because a wild wolf, even one

00:06:08.609 --> 00:06:11.759
raised by humans, is still a wild animal.

00:06:11.959 --> 00:06:14.239
It's unpredictable, it is

00:06:14.419 --> 00:06:16.589
aggressive, and it's very hard

00:06:16.609 --> 00:06:18.729
to keep in a "domestic" setting.

00:06:19.669 --> 00:06:22.329
Even if you raise a wolf puppy

00:06:22.509 --> 00:06:24.709
with care and affection, when it

00:06:24.709 --> 00:06:26.819
grows up, it becomes very clear

00:06:27.099 --> 00:06:29.179
that it is still a wild animal.

00:06:30.479 --> 00:06:32.799
Instead, the true story of

00:06:32.799 --> 00:06:36.119
how some wolves became dogs is

00:06:36.119 --> 00:06:38.859
likely one of self-domestication.

00:06:40.069 --> 00:06:42.039
As humans moved across the

00:06:42.039 --> 00:06:44.609
land, we left things behind:

00:06:44.949 --> 00:06:47.069
specifically, scraps of food.

00:06:47.529 --> 00:06:48.339
Leftovers.

00:06:49.379 --> 00:06:52.009
For a hungry wolf, a human

00:06:52.009 --> 00:06:53.889
campsite was a "buffet."

00:06:55.419 --> 00:06:59.129
Most wolves were too afraid of humans

00:06:59.339 --> 00:07:02.069
to get close, but a small number

00:07:02.079 --> 00:07:04.239
of them were naturally a little

00:07:04.249 --> 00:07:06.643
bit braver, a little bit "tamer."

00:07:07.763 --> 00:07:10.553
These wolves realised that if they

00:07:10.563 --> 00:07:13.353
stayed near humans, they didn't have

00:07:13.353 --> 00:07:16.103
to hunt as hard, because breakfast

00:07:16.283 --> 00:07:17.933
would be served automatically;

00:07:18.323 --> 00:07:20.783
they could scavenge our leftovers.

00:07:21.823 --> 00:07:22.893
Because they were better

00:07:22.903 --> 00:07:25.013
fed, they had more puppies.

00:07:25.533 --> 00:07:28.613
And because tameness is a genetic

00:07:28.653 --> 00:07:31.233
trait, their puppies were even

00:07:31.243 --> 00:07:33.423
braver and even friendlier.

00:07:34.613 --> 00:07:36.723
Scientists call this the

00:07:36.733 --> 00:07:39.133
"Survival of the Friendliest."

00:07:40.693 --> 00:07:42.613
Over thousands of years, a

00:07:42.933 --> 00:07:45.273
"partnership of convenience" formed.

00:07:45.763 --> 00:07:48.773
These friendly wolves acted as a

00:07:48.783 --> 00:07:51.993
natural alarm system, barking when

00:07:51.993 --> 00:07:53.783
a dangerous predator approached

00:07:53.793 --> 00:07:56.503
the camp at night, so humans were

00:07:56.713 --> 00:07:58.573
happy to be followed by wolves.

00:07:59.243 --> 00:08:01.673
And in return, they provided the

00:08:01.673 --> 00:08:04.583
animals with a steady source of protein.

00:08:05.793 --> 00:08:08.073
But friendliness alone doesn’t

00:08:08.073 --> 00:08:10.583
explain why wolves became dogs.

00:08:11.123 --> 00:08:12.623
Plenty of animals can

00:08:12.623 --> 00:08:14.253
become tolerant of humans.

00:08:14.833 --> 00:08:18.583
What makes dogs unusual, and what truly

00:08:18.583 --> 00:08:21.213
separates them from wolves, is how

00:08:21.213 --> 00:08:24.293
well they learned to understand humans.

00:08:25.503 --> 00:08:27.243
Modern studies have shown

00:08:27.243 --> 00:08:29.203
that dogs are remarkably good

00:08:29.443 --> 00:08:31.413
at reading human behaviour.

00:08:31.933 --> 00:08:34.423
They follow pointing gestures.

00:08:34.523 --> 00:08:37.133
They look to humans for guidance

00:08:37.323 --> 00:08:38.713
when faced with a problem.

00:08:39.513 --> 00:08:41.453
In some experiments, dogs

00:08:41.693 --> 00:08:44.453
outperform even chimpanzees at

00:08:44.493 --> 00:08:46.463
understanding basic human cues.

00:08:47.773 --> 00:08:51.143
And over time, dogs didn’t just

00:08:51.193 --> 00:08:53.743
adapt to living near humans.

00:08:54.183 --> 00:08:57.183
They adapted to living with humans.

00:08:57.443 --> 00:09:01.093
They evolved to fit into our social world.

00:09:02.223 --> 00:09:05.313
And as these animals changed their

00:09:05.313 --> 00:09:07.663
behaviour, something fascinating

00:09:07.893 --> 00:09:09.443
happened to their bodies.

00:09:10.373 --> 00:09:13.823
This is known as Domestication Syndrome.

00:09:15.113 --> 00:09:17.913
As we selected for "friendliness,"

00:09:18.383 --> 00:09:19.963
other physical changes

00:09:19.963 --> 00:09:22.139
followed, almost by accident.

00:09:22.969 --> 00:09:26.523
Their snouts, their noses, became shorter.

00:09:27.153 --> 00:09:28.933
Their teeth became smaller.

00:09:29.463 --> 00:09:31.473
Their ears, which were previously

00:09:31.493 --> 00:09:33.713
sharp and upright to catch the

00:09:33.713 --> 00:09:36.323
sound of prey, began to flop over.

00:09:37.073 --> 00:09:38.043
They even developed

00:09:38.263 --> 00:09:40.306
"patches" of white fur.

00:09:41.693 --> 00:09:43.423
And the changes weren't

00:09:43.433 --> 00:09:45.123
just on the outside.

00:09:45.713 --> 00:09:47.703
Inside their bodies, something

00:09:47.763 --> 00:09:49.823
even more remarkable was happening.

00:09:51.003 --> 00:09:53.743
Scientists have discovered that one of the

00:09:53.753 --> 00:09:56.613
biggest genetic differences between a wolf

00:09:56.663 --> 00:10:00.913
and a dog is the ability to digest starch,

00:10:01.113 --> 00:10:03.213
the carbohydrate you get from eating

00:10:03.213 --> 00:10:05.993
things like bread, rice and potatoes.

00:10:06.703 --> 00:10:09.863
And as humans moved from hunting

00:10:09.863 --> 00:10:12.223
to farming and started eating more

00:10:12.223 --> 00:10:15.483
bread and grains, the dogs that

00:10:15.483 --> 00:10:18.073
survived were the ones whose stomachs

00:10:18.123 --> 00:10:20.603
adapted to eat our leftovers.

00:10:21.093 --> 00:10:22.543
They literally evolved

00:10:22.833 --> 00:10:24.093
to share our dinner.

00:10:25.123 --> 00:10:27.923
And perhaps the most remarkable,

00:10:28.003 --> 00:10:30.293
or most manipulative, of the

00:10:30.293 --> 00:10:32.623
changes happened in their faces.

00:10:33.323 --> 00:10:35.643
Dogs have a tiny muscle above their

00:10:35.643 --> 00:10:38.533
eyes that wolves simply do not have.

00:10:39.383 --> 00:10:41.443
It allows them to raise their

00:10:41.463 --> 00:10:43.713
inner eyebrows to create what

00:10:43.713 --> 00:10:45.703
we call "puppy dog eyes."

00:10:46.283 --> 00:10:49.233
This expression mimics the look of a

00:10:49.233 --> 00:10:52.373
human infant, a baby, which triggers

00:10:52.373 --> 00:10:54.843
a nurturing response in our brains

00:10:54.843 --> 00:10:57.323
and makes us want to protect them.

00:10:58.413 --> 00:11:01.773
I love dogs, and if you are also a

00:11:01.793 --> 00:11:04.643
dog person, then what I’m describing

00:11:04.653 --> 00:11:07.003
doesn’t need any further explanation.

00:11:07.453 --> 00:11:10.213
And even if you are more of a cat

00:11:10.283 --> 00:11:12.633
person, it must be hard to look at a

00:11:12.723 --> 00:11:15.763
puppy making “that face” and not feel

00:11:15.773 --> 00:11:18.173
some sort of affection towards it.

00:11:18.823 --> 00:11:21.463
Now, you might be wondering: how do

00:11:21.463 --> 00:11:24.193
we know this "self-domestication"

00:11:24.413 --> 00:11:25.433
actually happened?

00:11:25.943 --> 00:11:28.603
Well, it's actually been put to the test

00:11:28.853 --> 00:11:31.513
a lot more recently than 10,000 years ago.

00:11:33.093 --> 00:11:35.553
In the 1950s, a Soviet

00:11:35.593 --> 00:11:38.223
scientist named Dmitry Belyaev

00:11:38.653 --> 00:11:40.603
decided to test this theory.

00:11:41.373 --> 00:11:45.623
He took wild silver foxes and performed

00:11:45.653 --> 00:11:48.483
a simple experiment: he only allowed

00:11:48.503 --> 00:11:51.403
the "tamest" foxes—the ones that

00:11:51.403 --> 00:11:53.713
didn’t try to bite him—to breed.

00:11:54.723 --> 00:11:58.253
Curiously, within just a few generations,

00:11:58.603 --> 00:12:01.693
the foxes didn’t just become friendly like

00:12:01.773 --> 00:12:05.773
dogs; they also started to look like dogs.

00:12:06.316 --> 00:12:08.303
Their ears began to flop,

00:12:08.503 --> 00:12:11.173
their tails began to wag, and

00:12:11.399 --> 00:12:13.173
their coats changed color.

00:12:14.413 --> 00:12:17.263
This experiment proved that when you

00:12:17.273 --> 00:12:20.363
select an animal for temperament—for

00:12:20.563 --> 00:12:24.193
being "nice"—nature seems to throw

00:12:24.193 --> 00:12:26.883
in these physical changes for free.

00:12:27.983 --> 00:12:30.613
And as for dogs, there wasn’t

00:12:30.623 --> 00:12:32.903
of course just one type of dog.

00:12:33.493 --> 00:12:35.453
As humans moved into different

00:12:35.473 --> 00:12:38.483
environments—from the frozen Arctic

00:12:38.503 --> 00:12:39.763
to the hot deserts of the Middle

00:12:39.763 --> 00:12:43.013
East—the dog adapted alongside us.

00:12:43.933 --> 00:12:46.813
And to reiterate, it’s believed that

00:12:46.813 --> 00:12:48.843
this was happening all over the world;

00:12:48.883 --> 00:12:51.433
it wasn’t specific to one region.

00:12:52.633 --> 00:12:54.783
What this meant was that we began to

00:12:54.783 --> 00:12:57.773
see the very first "specialised" dogs,

00:12:58.063 --> 00:13:01.693
dogs that were bred to do specific jobs.

00:13:02.393 --> 00:13:04.103
Dogs bred for hunting,

00:13:04.113 --> 00:13:07.023
with speed, stamina, and an

00:13:07.023 --> 00:13:09.083
exceptional sense of smell.

00:13:09.603 --> 00:13:12.603
Dogs bred to guard camps and later

00:13:12.603 --> 00:13:15.253
settlements, alert to danger and

00:13:15.253 --> 00:13:17.443
willing to defend their human group.

00:13:18.233 --> 00:13:21.523
And, crucially, dogs bred to help

00:13:21.523 --> 00:13:24.003
humans control other animals.

00:13:25.183 --> 00:13:28.403
When we began to domesticate sheep,

00:13:28.603 --> 00:13:31.913
goats, and cattle, dogs made this

00:13:31.913 --> 00:13:34.343
possible on a much larger scale.

00:13:35.123 --> 00:13:36.823
One person alone would

00:13:36.823 --> 00:13:39.173
struggle to contain a herd.

00:13:39.403 --> 00:13:42.573
But one person with a dog or with multiple

00:13:42.573 --> 00:13:45.203
dogs is a different kettle of fish.

00:13:46.193 --> 00:13:48.643
Herding dogs allowed humans to

00:13:48.643 --> 00:13:50.403
manage livestock efficiently,

00:13:50.793 --> 00:13:52.573
protect it from predators, and

00:13:52.603 --> 00:13:55.323
move it across long distances.

00:13:55.743 --> 00:13:58.683
And this mattered enormously.

00:13:59.153 --> 00:14:00.983
Because livestock meant a

00:14:01.003 --> 00:14:02.403
reliable source of food.

00:14:02.743 --> 00:14:05.163
Reliable food meant surplus.

00:14:05.303 --> 00:14:07.913
And surplus meant that humans no

00:14:07.913 --> 00:14:10.103
longer needed to spend every waking

00:14:10.133 --> 00:14:12.183
hour searching for their next meal.

00:14:12.753 --> 00:14:14.893
This, in turn, allowed

00:14:14.903 --> 00:14:16.043
settlements to grow.

00:14:16.493 --> 00:14:18.446
Villages became towns.

00:14:18.796 --> 00:14:20.466
Towns became cities.

00:14:21.116 --> 00:14:24.656
And through all of this, dogs were

00:14:24.656 --> 00:14:27.076
there, working alongside humans.

00:14:27.586 --> 00:14:28.226
They hunted.

00:14:28.726 --> 00:14:29.346
They guarded.

00:14:29.406 --> 00:14:30.606
They herded.

00:14:30.626 --> 00:14:33.296
They pulled sleds across frozen

00:14:33.296 --> 00:14:35.696
landscapes where no other animals could.

00:14:36.416 --> 00:14:38.776
In the Arctic, dogs made human life

00:14:38.776 --> 00:14:41.306
possible in places that would otherwise

00:14:41.306 --> 00:14:43.636
have been completely uninhabitable.

00:14:44.326 --> 00:14:47.136
In deserts, they protected camps at night.

00:14:47.486 --> 00:14:49.676
In forests, they tracked prey

00:14:49.866 --> 00:14:51.456
invisible to the human eye.

00:14:52.076 --> 00:14:53.976
Dogs didn’t just adapt

00:14:54.056 --> 00:14:55.576
to human civilisation.

00:14:56.006 --> 00:14:59.136
Human civilisation adapted with dogs.

00:15:00.006 --> 00:15:02.406
And for most of history, it was

00:15:02.406 --> 00:15:04.506
a working partnership, of course.

00:15:04.996 --> 00:15:07.336
There was surely affection, as you

00:15:07.336 --> 00:15:10.176
can see in the Odyssey, but the dog’s

00:15:10.236 --> 00:15:13.726
primary function was as a worker, not

00:15:13.976 --> 00:15:16.106
as someone to lie around you next to

00:15:16.106 --> 00:15:18.046
your feet and get its tummy tickled.

00:15:19.056 --> 00:15:21.626
And often, the partnership was

00:15:22.016 --> 00:15:24.266
neither gentle nor sentimental.

00:15:24.986 --> 00:15:27.156
Dogs were used in warfare.

00:15:27.706 --> 00:15:30.316
The Assyrians, the Romans, and

00:15:30.506 --> 00:15:32.566
later medieval armies all used

00:15:32.616 --> 00:15:34.966
large dogs to intimidate enemies,

00:15:35.326 --> 00:15:37.626
guard camps, and even fight.

00:15:38.776 --> 00:15:41.916
In many societies, powerful dogs became

00:15:41.926 --> 00:15:45.286
symbols of status and authority, owned

00:15:45.526 --> 00:15:47.956
only by elites, kings and queens.

00:15:48.406 --> 00:15:52.186
But even here, the pattern is the same.

00:15:52.616 --> 00:15:55.526
Dogs amplified human ability.

00:15:55.886 --> 00:15:57.866
They made humans more effective,

00:15:57.886 --> 00:16:00.626
more mobile, and more secure.

00:16:01.286 --> 00:16:03.566
A dog would be undyingly loyal

00:16:03.566 --> 00:16:05.596
to his master, but he could

00:16:05.596 --> 00:16:07.236
be vicious if ordered to be.

00:16:08.266 --> 00:16:10.686
However, it's perhaps a simplification

00:16:11.016 --> 00:16:13.666
to assume that dogs in the past were

00:16:13.686 --> 00:16:16.046
only valued for their "utility".

00:16:16.806 --> 00:16:20.346
In 1914, German archaeologists found

00:16:20.346 --> 00:16:23.516
a grave that dates back 14,000 years,

00:16:23.756 --> 00:16:25.976
to a time when you might have thought

00:16:26.106 --> 00:16:28.976
dogs had a purely functional purpose.

00:16:29.616 --> 00:16:33.176
Inside were a man, a woman, and a dog.

00:16:33.836 --> 00:16:36.396
But here is the interesting part:

00:16:37.076 --> 00:16:39.886
scientists analysed the dog’s teeth

00:16:40.246 --> 00:16:42.146
and found that it had been very

00:16:42.146 --> 00:16:44.776
sick for a long time before it died.

00:16:45.303 --> 00:16:47.116
This dog could not have hunted.

00:16:47.339 --> 00:16:48.986
It could not have guarded the camp.

00:16:49.086 --> 00:16:51.936
It was "useless" in a survival sense.

00:16:52.846 --> 00:16:55.556
Yet, the humans had kept it alive,

00:16:55.866 --> 00:16:58.086
feeding it and cleaning it for months.

00:16:58.946 --> 00:17:01.226
This is clear evidence us that the

00:17:01.246 --> 00:17:04.686
emotional bond we saw with Argos in the

00:17:04.736 --> 00:17:08.116
Odyssey wasn't some kind of new invention;

00:17:08.396 --> 00:17:10.526
it was already thousands of years old.

00:17:11.786 --> 00:17:14.656
Dogs might have been primarily workers,

00:17:14.896 --> 00:17:17.656
but even going back tens of thousands

00:17:17.656 --> 00:17:20.236
of years, humans clearly weren’t

00:17:20.266 --> 00:17:22.696
able to resist those puppy dog eyes

00:17:22.746 --> 00:17:25.006
or the loyal affection of a canine

00:17:25.006 --> 00:17:27.316
companion any more than we are today.

00:17:28.236 --> 00:17:31.456
Still, there are some examples of humans

00:17:31.466 --> 00:17:34.116
keeping dogs as pets, like we do today,

00:17:34.476 --> 00:17:37.986
but this was typically a luxury reserved

00:17:38.026 --> 00:17:40.466
for those at the very top of society.

00:17:41.476 --> 00:17:44.176
If you are a keen student of British

00:17:44.176 --> 00:17:46.686
history, or you listened to episode

00:17:46.686 --> 00:17:50.196
187 and have a fantastic memory,

00:17:50.606 --> 00:17:53.096
you may remember the last moments

00:17:53.156 --> 00:17:55.906
of the life of Mary Queen of Scots.

00:17:56.736 --> 00:17:58.236
She was beheaded on the

00:17:58.246 --> 00:17:59.916
orders of Queen Elizabeth.

00:18:00.376 --> 00:18:03.576
So the story goes, after the executioner

00:18:03.586 --> 00:18:06.546
struck, a little dog scuttled out

00:18:06.766 --> 00:18:09.206
from under her petticoats and refused

00:18:09.386 --> 00:18:12.106
to leave her body, lying between

00:18:12.106 --> 00:18:14.316
her severed head and shoulders.

00:18:15.073 --> 00:18:17.253
The poor thing was covered in her

00:18:17.253 --> 00:18:20.323
blood and had to be forcibly removed.

00:18:20.813 --> 00:18:23.573
It’s a grisly tale, but yet

00:18:23.603 --> 00:18:26.533
another reminder of the longevity

00:18:26.673 --> 00:18:28.673
of this human-canine bond.

00:18:29.663 --> 00:18:32.873
Now, over time, as societies changed,

00:18:33.183 --> 00:18:35.853
the role of dogs began to change too.

00:18:36.353 --> 00:18:39.053
With industrialisation, urbanisation,

00:18:39.073 --> 00:18:41.483
and modern weapons, humans

00:18:41.683 --> 00:18:44.203
relied less on dogs for survival.

00:18:44.963 --> 00:18:48.283
Most dogs lost their “jobs”, but in

00:18:48.283 --> 00:18:50.413
what we might perhaps call an early

00:18:50.413 --> 00:18:53.663
form of universal basic canine income,

00:18:54.077 --> 00:18:57.363
dogs moved from the field into the home.

00:18:57.733 --> 00:18:59.983
From tools to companions.

00:19:00.563 --> 00:19:02.803
With their roles redundant, they were

00:19:02.813 --> 00:19:05.993
allowed to put their paws up and relax.

00:19:07.233 --> 00:19:09.493
In the 19th century, particularly in

00:19:09.503 --> 00:19:12.903
Europe, and most markedly in Victorian

00:19:12.913 --> 00:19:15.583
England, dogs were increasingly

00:19:15.583 --> 00:19:18.013
kept purely for companionship.

00:19:18.533 --> 00:19:20.553
Dogs were no longer workers;

00:19:20.583 --> 00:19:22.443
they were family members.

00:19:22.583 --> 00:19:24.493
They were given names.

00:19:24.513 --> 00:19:26.153
They slept indoors.

00:19:26.393 --> 00:19:28.113
They were mourned when they died.

00:19:29.193 --> 00:19:31.433
But the Victorians didn't just

00:19:31.453 --> 00:19:33.303
move dogs into the living room;

00:19:33.563 --> 00:19:35.473
they fundamentally redesigned them.

00:19:36.883 --> 00:19:40.553
Before the 1800s, 'breeds' were

00:19:40.813 --> 00:19:43.603
loose categories based on jobs.

00:19:44.163 --> 00:19:47.903
But in 1873, the first Kennel

00:19:47.903 --> 00:19:49.783
Club was founded in London.

00:19:50.583 --> 00:19:53.153
Humans began to write 'breed

00:19:53.163 --> 00:19:56.263
standards–strict rules on exactly

00:19:56.273 --> 00:19:58.763
how a dog’s tail should curl

00:19:58.763 --> 00:20:00.573
or how long its nose should be.

00:20:01.773 --> 00:20:04.493
By closing the 'gene pool' and only

00:20:04.493 --> 00:20:07.683
allowing 'purebreds' to mate, we created

00:20:07.683 --> 00:20:10.553
the incredible physical variety we see

00:20:10.553 --> 00:20:13.623
today—from the tiny Chihuahua to the

00:20:13.623 --> 00:20:16.383
massive Great Dane—this was created

00:20:16.703 --> 00:20:19.683
all in just a few human generations.

00:20:20.773 --> 00:20:22.693
And the trend of dog

00:20:22.773 --> 00:20:24.803
ownership only accelerated.

00:20:25.403 --> 00:20:28.063
What began in Victorian drawing rooms

00:20:28.363 --> 00:20:30.103
spread across the industrialised

00:20:30.123 --> 00:20:32.063
world throughout the 20th century.

00:20:32.583 --> 00:20:35.203
As countries industrialised and grew

00:20:35.203 --> 00:20:37.053
wealthier, particularly after World

00:20:37.053 --> 00:20:39.843
War II, more and more people had the

00:20:39.843 --> 00:20:42.133
disposable income to keep an animal

00:20:42.143 --> 00:20:44.513
that served no practical purpose.

00:20:45.743 --> 00:20:47.233
And what had once been a

00:20:47.243 --> 00:20:49.553
luxury of the Victorian upper

00:20:49.553 --> 00:20:51.823
classes became a global norm.

00:20:53.083 --> 00:20:55.923
For most of human history, keeping a dog

00:20:56.083 --> 00:20:58.443
that did no work at all would have seemed

00:20:58.513 --> 00:21:01.943
not just unusual, but irresponsible.

00:21:02.613 --> 00:21:06.543
But by the 1960s and 70s, in countries

00:21:06.543 --> 00:21:08.473
across Europe, North America,

00:21:08.483 --> 00:21:11.463
and parts of Asia, the "pet dog"

00:21:11.843 --> 00:21:14.313
had become normal, even expected.

00:21:14.713 --> 00:21:17.293
A home wasn't quite complete without one.

00:21:18.173 --> 00:21:21.073
And today, well, dog ownership is huge.

00:21:21.543 --> 00:21:23.993
Sure, there are still some countries and

00:21:23.993 --> 00:21:26.243
societies where dogs are not popular,

00:21:26.663 --> 00:21:29.533
whether that’s for religious or societal

00:21:29.533 --> 00:21:32.143
reasons, but these are a minority.

00:21:32.783 --> 00:21:35.513
Globally around 30% of

00:21:35.513 --> 00:21:37.073
households have a dog.

00:21:37.623 --> 00:21:40.513
People spend thousands of Euros on

00:21:40.513 --> 00:21:42.863
their dogs, and according to one

00:21:42.863 --> 00:21:45.963
report, spending on pets is scheduled

00:21:46.183 --> 00:21:51.033
to reach $500 billion per year by 2030.

00:21:51.703 --> 00:21:54.693
Yes, that includes other animals too, but

00:21:54.723 --> 00:21:56.743
dogs are the world’s most popular pet,

00:21:57.113 --> 00:21:59.183
and get the lion’s share of the spend.

00:22:00.413 --> 00:22:02.363
If you have a dog, you probably

00:22:02.363 --> 00:22:04.563
need no reminder as to why.

00:22:05.263 --> 00:22:08.503
Odysseus knew it 3,000 years ago, the

00:22:08.503 --> 00:22:11.803
Victorians knew it 150 years ago, and

00:22:12.013 --> 00:22:14.343
there is certainly a good reason that

00:22:14.353 --> 00:22:17.313
almost every language has some variant

00:22:17.403 --> 00:22:19.933
on the phrase “man’s best friend”.

00:22:21.543 --> 00:22:23.443
OK, then, that is it for today's

00:22:23.463 --> 00:22:26.473
episode on dogs, our faithful, canine

00:22:26.473 --> 00:22:29.193
partners for tens of thousands of years.

00:22:29.533 --> 00:22:31.333
As a reminder, this was part

00:22:31.333 --> 00:22:33.373
one of a three-part mini-series

00:22:33.583 --> 00:22:34.913
on the theme of animals.

00:22:35.213 --> 00:22:38.023
Next up we have an animal I must confess

00:22:38.023 --> 00:22:40.363
I don’t enjoy the company of as much

00:22:40.623 --> 00:22:42.893
as I do dogs, and that is the cat.

00:22:43.223 --> 00:22:45.053
And in part three, it’ll be the

00:22:45.063 --> 00:22:48.303
fire-breathing, mythical world of dragons.

00:22:48.653 --> 00:22:50.443
You've been listening to English Learning

00:22:50.443 --> 00:22:53.113
for Curious Minds by Leonardo English.

00:22:53.453 --> 00:22:56.163
I'm Alastair Budge, you stay safe, and

00:22:56.163 --> 00:22:58.373
I'll catch you in the next episode.

